# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: canopen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:canopen/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:canopen/canopen] The basic CANopen device and communication profiles are given in the CiA 301 specification released by CAN in Automation.
[src:canopen/canopen] Profiles for more specialized devices are built on top of this basic profile, and are specified in numerous other standards released by CAN in Automation, such as CiA 401 for I/O-modules and CiA 402 for motion control.
[src:canopen/canopen] Every CANopen device has to implement certain standard features in its controlling software.
[src:canopen/canopen] CANopen devices must have an object dictionary, which is used for configuration and communication with the device.
[src:canopen/canopen] The composite datatypes can be subindexed with an 8-bit index; the value in subindex 0 of an array or record indicates the number of elements in the data structure, and is of type UNSIGNED8.
[src:canopen/canopen] For example, the device communication parameters, standardized in the basic device profile CiA 301 are mapped in the index range 0x1000–0x1FFF ("communication profile area").
[src:canopen/canopen] Given suitable tools, the content of the object dictionary of a device, based on an electronic data sheet (EDS), can be customized to a device configuration file (DCF) to integrate the device into a specific CANopen network.
[src:canopen/canopen] According to CiA 306, the format of the EDS-file is the INI file format.
[src:canopen/canopen] There is an upcoming XML-style format, that is described in CiA 311.
[src:canopen/canopen] CAN bus, the data link layer of CANopen, can only transmit short packages consisting of an 11-bit id, a remote transmission request (RTR) bit and 0 to 8 bytes of data.
[src:canopen/canopen] The CANopen standard divides the 11-bit CAN frame id into a 4-bit function code and 7-bit CANopen node ID.
[src:canopen/canopen] This limits the number of devices in a CANopen network to 127 (0 being reserved for broadcast).
[src:canopen/canopen] An extension to the CAN bus standard (CAN 2.0 B) allows extended frame ids of 29 bits, but in practice CANopen networks big enough to need the extended id range are rarely seen.
[src:canopen/canopen] In CANopen the 11-bit id of a CAN-frame is known as communication object identifier, or COB-ID.
[src:canopen/canopen] In case of a transmission collision, the bus arbitration used in the CAN bus allows the frame with the smallest id to be transmitted first and without a delay.
[src:canopen/canopen] Using a low code number for time critical functions ensures the lowest possible delay.
[src:canopen/canopen] The data frame with an 11-bit identifier is also called "base frame format".
[src:canopen/canopen] The default CAN-ID mapping sorts frames by attributing a function code (NMT, SYNC, EMCY, PDO, SDO...) to the first 4 bits, so that critical functions are given priority.
[src:canopen/canopen] This mapping can however be customized for special purposes (except for NMT and SDO, required for basic communication).
[src:canopen/canopen] The standard reserves certain CAN-IDs to network management and SDO transfers.
[src:canopen/canopen] Some function codes and CAN-IDs have to be mapped to standard functionality after device initialization, but can be configured for other uses later.
[src:canopen/canopen] For simple network structures, CANopen supports a predefined allocation of message identifiers.
[src:canopen/canopen] The transmit and receive directions are from the device's point of view.
[src:canopen/canopen] So a query to a device on the network would send a 0x600+nodeid and get back a 0x580+nodeid.
[src:canopen/canopen] Different kinds of communication models are used in the messaging between CANopen nodes.
[src:canopen/canopen] In a **master/slave** relationship, one CANopen node is designated as the master, which sends or requests data from the slaves.
[src:canopen/canopen] The NMT protocol is an example of a master/slave communication model.
[src:canopen/canopen] A **client/server** relationship is implemented in the SDO protocol, where the SDO client sends data (the object dictionary index and subindex) to an SDO server, which replies with one or more SDO packages containing the requested data (the contents of the object dictionary at the given index).
[src:canopen/canopen] A **producer/consumer** model is used in the Heartbeat and Node Guarding protocols.
[src:canopen/canopen] In the *push-model* of producer/consumer, the producer sends data to the consumer without a specific request, whereas in the *pull model*, the consumer has to request the data from the producer.
[src:canopen/canopen] The NMT protocols are used to issue state machine change commands (e.g. to start and stop the devices), detect remote device bootups and error conditions.
[src:canopen/canopen] The **Module control protocol** is used by the NMT master to change the state of the devices.
[src:canopen/canopen] The CAN-frame COB-ID of this protocol is always 0, meaning that it has a function code 0 and node ID 0, which means that every node in the network will process this message.
[src:canopen/canopen] The actual node ID, to which the command is meant to, is given in the data part of the message (at the second byte).
[src:canopen/canopen] This can also be 0, meaning that all the devices on the bus should go to the indicated state.
[src:canopen/canopen] The **Heartbeat protocol** is used to monitor the nodes in the network and verify that they are alive.
[src:canopen/canopen] A heartbeat producer (usually a slave device) periodically sends a message with the binary function code of 1110 and its node ID (COB-ID19 = 0x700 + node ID).
[src:canopen/canopen] The data part of the frame contains a byte indicating the node status.
[src:canopen/canopen] The heartbeat consumer reads these messages.
[src:canopen/canopen] If the messages fail to arrive within a certain time limit (defined in the object dictionary of the devices) the consumer can take action to, for example, reset the device or indicate an error.
[src:canopen/canopen] CANopen devices are required to make the transition from the state Initializing to Pre-operational automatically during bootup.
[src:canopen/canopen] When this transition is made, a single heartbeat message is sent to the bus.
[src:canopen/canopen] A response/reply-style (pull model) protocol, called node guarding, exists for slave monitoring.
[src:canopen/canopen] The SDO protocol is used for setting and for reading values from the object dictionary of a remote device.
[src:canopen/canopen] The device whose object dictionary is accessed is the SDO server and the device accessing the remote device is the SDO client.
[src:canopen/canopen] The communication is always initiated by the SDO client.
[src:canopen/canopen] In CANopen terminology, communication is viewed from the SDO server, so that a read from an object dictionary results in an SDO upload and a write to a dictionary entry is an SDO download.
[src:canopen/canopen] Because the object dictionary values can be larger than the eight bytes limit of a CAN frame, the SDO protocol implements segmentation and desegmentation of longer messages.
[src:canopen/canopen] Actually, there are two of these protocols: SDO download/upload and SDO Block download/upload.
[src:canopen/canopen] The SDO block transfer is a newer addition to standard, which allows large amounts of data to be transferred with slightly less protocol overhead.
[src:canopen/canopen] The COB-IDs of the respective SDO transfer messages from client to server and server to client can be set in the object dictionary.
[src:canopen/canopen] Up to 128 SDO servers can be set up in the object dictionary at addresses 0x1200 - 0x127F.
[src:canopen/canopen] Similarly, the SDO client connections of the device can be configured with variables at 0x1280 - 0x12FF.
[src:canopen/canopen] However the *pre-defined connection set* defines an SDO channel which can be used even just after bootup (in the Pre-operational state) to configure the device.
[src:canopen/canopen] The COB-IDs of this channel are 0x600 + node ID for receiving and 0x580 + node ID for transmitting.
[src:canopen/canopen] To initiate a download, the SDO client sends the following data in a CAN message with the 'receive' COB-ID of the SDO channel.
[src:canopen/canopen] The Process Data Object protocol is used to process real time data among various nodes.
[src:canopen/canopen] You can transfer up to 8 bytes (64 bits) of data per one PDO either from or to the device.
[src:canopen/canopen] One PDO can contain multiple object dictionary entries and the objects within one PDO are configurable using the mapping and parameter object dictionary entries.
[src:canopen/canopen] There are two kinds of PDOs: transmit and receive PDOs (TPDO and RPDO).
[src:canopen/canopen] The former is for data coming from the device (the device is a data producer) and the latter is for data going to the device (the device is a data consumer); that is, with RPDO you can send data to the device and with TPDO you can read data from the device.
[src:canopen/canopen] In the pre-defined connection set there are identifiers for four TPDOs and four RPDOs available.
[src:canopen/canopen] With configuration, 512 PDOs are possible.
[src:canopen/canopen] PDOs can be sent synchronously or asynchronously.
[src:canopen/canopen] Synchronous PDOs are sent after the SYNC message whereas asynchronous messages are sent after internal or external trigger.
[src:canopen/canopen] For example, you can make a request to a device to transmit TPDO that contains data you need by sending an empty TPDO with the RTR flag (if the device is configured to accept TPDO requests).
[src:canopen/canopen] With RPDOs you can, for example, start two devices simultaneously.
[src:canopen/canopen] You only need to map the same RPDO into two or more different devices and make sure those RPDOs are mapped with the same COB-ID.
[src:canopen/canopen] The Sync-Producer provides the synchronization-signal for the Sync-Consumer.
[src:canopen/canopen] When the Sync-Consumer receive the signal they start carrying out their synchronous tasks.
[src:canopen/canopen] In general, the fixing of the transmission time of synchronous PDO messages coupled with the periodicity of transmission of the Sync Object guarantees that sensor devices may arrange to sample process variables and that actuator devices may apply their actuation in a coordinated fashion.
[src:canopen/canopen] The identifier of the Sync Object is available at index 1005h.
[src:canopen/canopen] Usually the Time-Stamp object represents a time as a 6-byte field: a count of milliseconds after midnight (at most 27 bits, stored in a 32-bit field), and an unsigned 16-bit number of days since January 1, 1984.
[src:canopen/canopen] Some time critical applications especially in large networks with reduced transmission rates require very accurate synchronization; it may be necessary to synchronize the local clocks with an accuracy in the order of microseconds.
[src:canopen/canopen] This is achieved by using the optional high resolution synchronization protocol which employs a special form of timestamp message to adjust the inevitable drift of the local clocks.
[src:canopen/canopen] The high-resolution timestamp is encoded as unsigned32 with a resolution of 1 microsecond which means that the time counter restarts every 72 minutes.
[src:canopen/canopen] It is configured by mapping the high resolution time-stamp (object 1013h) into a PDO.
[src:canopen/canopen] Emergency messages are triggered by the occurrence of a device internal fatal error situation and are transmitted from the concerned application device to the other devices with high priority.
[src:canopen/canopen] This makes them suitable for interrupt type error alerts.
[src:canopen/canopen] An Emergency Telegram may be sent only once per ‘error event’, i.e. the emergency messages must not be repeated.
[src:canopen/canopen] As long as no new errors occur on a device no further emergency message must be sent.
[src:canopen/canopen] By means of CANopen Communication Profile defined emergency error codes, the error register and device specific additional information are specified in the device profiles.
[src:canopen/canopen] Sample trace of communications between a master and two pressure transducer slaves configured for id 1 and node ID 2.
[src:canopen/canopen] Electronic Data Sheet (EDS) is a file format, defined in CiA306, that describes the communication behaviour and the object dictionary entries of a device.
[src:canopen/canopen] This allows tools such as service tools, configuration tools, development tools, and others to handle the devices properly.
[src:canopen/canopen] Those EDS files are mandatory for passing the CiA CANopen conformance test.
[src:canopen/canopen] Since end of 2007 a new XML based format called XDD is defined in CiA311.
[src:canopen/canopen] XDD is conformant to ISO standard 15745.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Typically, a datasheet is created by the manufacturer and begins with an introductory page describing the rest of the document, followed by listings of specific characteristics, with further information on the connectivity of the devices.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] In cases where there is relevant source code to include, it is usually attached near the end of the document or separated into another file.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Datasheets are created, stored, and distributed via product information management or product data management systems.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Depending on the specific purpose, a datasheet may offer an average value, a typical value, a typical range, engineering tolerances, or a nominal value.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The type and source of data are usually stated on the datasheet.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] A datasheet is usually used for commercial or technical communication to describe the characteristics of an item or product.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] It can be published by the manufacturer to help people choose products or to help use the products.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] By contrast, a technical specification is an explicit set of requirements to be satisfied by a material, product, or service.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The ideal datasheet specifies characteristics in a formal structure, according to a strict taxonomy, that allows the information to be processed by a machine.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Such machine readable descriptions can facilitate information retrieval, display, design, testing, interfacing, verification, system discovery, and e-commerce.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Examples include Open Icecat data-sheets, transducer electronic data sheets for describing sensor characteristics, and electronic device descriptions in CANopen or descriptions in markup languages, such as SensorML.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] A product data sheet (PDS), like any datasheet, has a different data model per category.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] In Open Icecat, the global open catalog or open content project in which hundreds of manufacturers and thousands of e-commerce sellers participate, the data models of tens of thousands of taxonomy classes are defined, and millions of free PDSs can be found conforming these data-sheet data models.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] A material safety data sheet (MSDS), safety data sheet (SDS), or product safety data sheet (PSDS) is an important component of product stewardship and occupational safety and health.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] These are required by agencies such as OSHA in its Hazard Communication Standard, 29 C.F.R.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] It provides workers with ways to allow them to work in a safe manner and gives them physical data (melting point, boiling point, flash point, etc.), toxicity, health effects, first aid, reactivity, storage, disposal, protective equipment, and spill-handling procedures.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The MSDSs differ from country to country, as different countries have different regulations.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] In some jurisdictions, it is compulsory for the SDS to state the chemical's risks, safety, and effect on the environment.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The SDSs are a commonly used classification for logging information on chemicals, chemical compounds, and chemical mixtures.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The SDSs often include the safe use of the chemical and the hazardous nature of the chemical.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Anytime chemicals are used these datasheets will be found.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] There is a need to have an internationally recognized symbol when describing hazardous substances.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Labels can include hazard symbols such as the European Union standard black diagonal cross on an orange background, used to denote a harmful substance.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] The purpose of an SDS is not so that the general public will have a knowledge of how to read and understand it, but more so that it can be used in an occupational setting to allow workers to be able to work with it.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Datasheets and pages are available for specific properties of chemicals in chemical elements data references: example, melting points of the elements (data page).
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Specific materials have technical data in individual sheets such as ethanol: this includes subjects such as structure and properties, thermodynamic properties, spectral data, vapor pressure, etc.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Other chemical datasheets are available from individual producers of chemicals, often on their web pages.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] Datasheets for automobiles may be described under several names such as features, specs, engineering data, technical summary, etc.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] They help communicate the technical information about a car to potential buyers and are useful for comparisons with similar cars.
[src:canopen/electronic-data-sheet] They might include: critical inside and outside dimensions, weight, fuel efficiency, engine and drive train, towing capability, safety features and options, warranty, etc.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:canopen/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:canopen/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:canopen/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:canopen/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Typically the position or velocity of machines are controlled using some type of device such as a hydraulic pump, linear actuator, or electric motor, generally a servo.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Motion control is an important part of robotics and CNC machine tools, however in these instances it is more complex than when used with specialized machines, where the kinematics are usually simpler.
[src:canopen/motion-control] The latter is often called General Motion Control (GMC).
[src:canopen/motion-control] Motion control is widely used in the packaging, printing, textile, semiconductor production, and assembly industries.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Motion Control encompasses every technology related to the movement of objects.
[src:canopen/motion-control] It covers every motion system from micro-sized systems such as silicon-type micro induction actuators to micro-siml systems such as a space platform.
[src:canopen/motion-control] But, these days, the focus of motion control is the special control technology of motion systems with electric actuators such as dc/ac servo motors.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Control of robotic manipulators is also included in the field of motion control because most of robotic manipulators are driven by electrical servo motors and the key objective is the control of motion.
[src:canopen/motion-control] The interface between the motion controller and drives it control is very critical when coordinated motion is required, as it must provide tight synchronization.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Historically the only open interface was an analog signal, until open interfaces were developed that satisfied the requirements of coordinated motion control, the first being SERCOS in 1991 which is now enhanced to SERCOS III.
[src:canopen/motion-control] Later interfaces capable of motion control include Ethernet/IP, Profinet IRT, Ethernet Powerlink, and EtherCAT.
